From now until then I’ll be sharing recipes and interviews from the book here and in my newsletter. 
This week a fav to turn any ☹️citrus into a treat: January Cranberry Orange Cake
Heat oven to 400F
Boil any citrus (in this case 6 shrively clementines)
Purée 
Mix 6 eggs, 1 cup sugar, 1 1/2 cup almond flour, 1 tsp baking powder, and 1 cup citrus purée 
Pour into a greased and lined 9” cake pan
Top w/ 1 cup cranberries
Bake until a knife comes out clean (about 50-60 minutes)
Flip out of the pan and munch
PS: I’ve also used frozen raspberries, blueberries, or rhubarb to equal delight. 
Recipe inspired by the one and only @beardfoundation

Hot take: frozen fruit is really good.
This peach-blueberry cobbler from Pulp is just as good made with frozen blueberries and peaches (I buy from @mifarmtofreezer ).
The cobbler batter recipe is straight from my mentor Rodger Bowser of @zingermansdeli fame.
1 cup milk (oatmilk is great)
1 cup sugar
1 cup all purpose flour
1 Tbsp baking powder
Whisk it all together to make a pourable batter
Pour the batter over 2 lbs of fruit in a 9x9 inch baking dish
Dot with 4 Tbsp butter and an extra sprinkle of sugar
Then bake at 350F until golden brown, usually about 45 min
I generally serve with a big dollop of sour cream but that’s optional.
Complete recipe in #pulpcookbook

As the publication day for Pulp nears, I want to introduce some of the people who made all three cookbooks possible.
First up, meet EE Berger, the woman behind the camera for Pulp, Ruffage, and Grist. I can’t imagine these books without her creative guiding hand, generous nature, and good humor. She is beautiful in person, in spirit, and in work. Follow her @eeberger for a daily dose of beauty in your feed.
These are her (hard-chosen) favorite images from Pulp, Ruffage, and Grist respectively. 
#pulpcookbook #preorder #foodphotography

I thought good styling was all Elmer’s glue and painted on grill marks, but Mollie Hayward taught me it isn’t tricks. Just a keen eye for color, prop, and placement.
For both Pulp and Grist she took the humblest of ingredients and styled them into chapter headers that are simple, beautiful, and interesting. We (Emily, Mollie, and myself) went round and round on what the chapter headers should be before landing on monochromatic glamor shots of each ingredient. Mollie then crafted these scenes, often on backgrounds she made herself to match, and looked at each one in context w/ the other to keep them interesting— a solo pear after a pile of grapes, a little bite out of one apricot, not afraid to Georgia O’Keeffe a melon.
Ruffage, Grist, and now Pulp are only beautiful because of her guiding hand and prop curation. Follow @mollierebeccahayward for more food glamor alongside some doggie feel good. 
#foodphotography #fruit #georgiaokeeffe #bite #cookbook #pulpcookbook

Pulp’s rhubarb upside down cake is inspired by Tim Mazurek’s pineapple version. I cannot imagine this book without Tim’s contributions. He is my best friend. He has inspired me through his years of writing on his blog, Lottie + Doof. He gave me this cake recipe. He wrote the most beautiful foreword to the book paying tribute to our friendship and our beloved Midwest. He has fielded every insecure question w/ patience and grace (mostly). He is funny and kind and suffers no fools. This book (and I) am better for it. 

He said he is most excited for the Baker’s Tool Kit (the over 100 recipes to make a million fruit desserts), the interviews (especially the one w/ Abby Schilling from @mickklugfarm ), and the savory recipes (like pork chops w/ poached rhubarb and rye spaetzle).

What I’m most excited about is you all getting to know him and his work. To celebrate him, I’m giving away a copy of Pulp so you can read the foreword and a cake plate for when you make his upside down cake. To enter: follow both of our accounts @timmazurek and @abraberens and tag your best friend who makes you better. This #giveaway is now closed. Congrats @saltootd5 !

As we get closer and closer to rounding the bend on winter, it’s only natural to begin growing tired of our winter veggies and fruits. As much as they get us through the cold months, even we can admit they begin to get old after awhile! It’s in times like these that we say one, go for the oft overlooked fruits and veg and two, get creative! Abra Berens, chef and author who kicked off our @kalnyc x Greenmarket Book Signing season today with her new cookbook, Pulp: A Practical Guide to Cooking with Fruit, is a major proponent of incorporating quince into your life to shake up the winter fruit routine. “Quince is a nice answer to the endless, endless apples that we have,” Abra says.

P.S. If you missed Abra at market today, you can find signed copies of her book at Kitchen Arts & Letters!

My fav part of this beet carpaccio w/ fresh strawberries is the candied fennel seeds scattered all over the top. Inspired by the anise candies in Indian restaurants, these little crunchers are a surprising addition to just about anything. 
To make:
In a small frying pan, over medium heat, combine 2 Tbsp sugar w/ 2 Tbsp water and reduce until syrupy. Then add 1/4 cup fennel seeds and stir continuously until the mixture crystallizes. Finish w/ a 1/4 tsp salt and then remove from the heat to let cool. They store indefinitely at room temperature for your scattering delight. 
Complete recipe in Pulp, which comes out in TWO days. Preorders are still available and starting to ship. Otherwise hope to see you at some of the events planned over the next couple of months!

My favorite moment yesterday was getting a quiet moment w/ Lark to flip through the pages of Pulp and feel the fullness of life.
20 years ago today my mom died, and my family felt hollowed out and gutted in a way that I wasn’t sure would heal.
We heal even if imperfectly. We move forward, and we can hold both fullness and emptiness at the same time.
Cheers to Jo Karyl Witte Berens, the life you lived and the love you gave us. Cheers to Lark, who has taught me a bit more about you.

Reviews, on @amazon @goodreads or anywhere, help others find the book. So if you’re willing to take the time, leaving Pulp a review helps me out! People always ask, “do you cook like this at home?” The answer is yes and no. Style is the same. Presentation and portion are very different.

Home: dried Bea pasta, preserved tomatoes, spinach, morels, and fresh mozzarella.

And just like that, it’s soup season.
Our favorite squash soup recipe 👇
1 large or 2 medium squash, cut in half
4 cloves garlic, minced
1 inch piece fresh ginger, peeled and minced
1 cayenne pepper, cut in half and seeded
1 can full fat coconut milk
1/4 cup pumpkin seeds, toasted
Cilantro leaves (optional)
Heat oven to 400F
Crack the squash in half, and roast cut side down, seeds and all, until the squash is soft
Remove from the oven and let cool
Meanwhile, in a soup pot, heat a large glug of neutral oil over medium heat
Add the garlic, ginger, and cayenne with a big pinch of salt and sauté until soft and fragrant
Remove the seeds from the squash and scoop the flesh into the soup pot
Add enough water to cover, bring to a boil
Remove from the heat, discard the cayenne, and transfer to a blender to purée
Whisk in the coconut milk (reserving a couple of spoonfuls to garnish), taste, and adjust seasoning adding more salt or a squeeze of lemon as needed
To serve divvy between bowls, drizzle the remaining coconut milk all over, scatter the pumpkin seeds and dig in!

Attention all tinned-fishionados: please meet #bottarga — salt cured mullet roe. If you like anchovy, you’ll probably like it grated over pasta (bucatini from @carosellopasta pictured) or scrambled eggs or popcorn. It is briny, shelf stable, endlessly riffable, and worth some renewed attention. And thus concludes my bottarga PSA.
